{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"Installation","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Installation"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"TagKit can be installed with the Swift Package Manager:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":null,"code":["https:\/\/github.com\/danielsaidi\/TagKit.git"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"or with CocoaPods:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":null,"code":["pod TagKit"]},{"anchor":"Tagging-with-TagKit","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Tagging with TagKit"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Before we look at tagging, let’s start with looking at slugifying strings, which is the process of converting a string to a slug by removing unsupported characters and replacing whitespace with a separator."}]},{"anchor":"Slugifying-strings","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Slugifying strings"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can see slugified strings in action in many web urls, where the page date and title is often slugified to create a unique valid url that also describes the content."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In TagKit, the "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/TagKit\/documentation\/TagKit\/Slugifiable"},{"type":"text","text":" protocol describes a slugifyable type:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["public protocol Slugifiable {","","    var slugifiableValue: String { get }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String"},{"type":"text","text":" implements this protocol by default, by returning itself as the slugifiable value."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Once a type implements "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/TagKit\/documentation\/TagKit\/Slugifiable"},{"type":"text","text":", it can be slugified with the "},{"type":"codeVoice","co